<DESCRIPT>  RELIGION; BRIEF  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Drew Christiansen, a Jesuit Bannan research professor in applied ethics at
Santa Clara University, is the featured speaker at a program examining ethical
implications and consequences of the Persian Gulf war, 12:30 p.m. Wednesday,
at Washington Square, Room 109, San Jose State University.;    His talk, "Just
War of Non-Violence? Evolution of Western Thought on War and Peace," is the
second in a three-part series sponsored by the SJS campus ministry. Sherna
Berger Gluck, director of the oral history program at California State
University in Long Beach, gives the final address, "Illusions of Gender
Solidarity: Palestinian and Israeli Women in Dialogue," on May 8.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Religion &amp; Ethics  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SJS TALK FOCUSES ON THE ETHICS OF THE GULF
WAR  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Briefs  </MEMO>
<TEXT>      NEW SENIOR PASTOR;  South Bay Christian Center, 1134 Miramonte Ave.,
Mountain View, will welcome its new senior pastor, D. Ronald Bailey, when he
leads his first services at 10:45 a.m. and 6 p.m. Sunday.;    The former
pastor of the Allison Park First Assembly Church of God in a suburb of
Pittsburgh, Bailey's congregation grew from 25 to 800 during his 23-year
pastorate there.;     QUILTING CONFERENCE; Three hundred women from South San
Jose, Gilroy and Hollister gathered March 23 at the Morgan Hill Stake, Church
of Jesus Christ Latter-day Saints, for the 11th annual Woman's Conference on
the theme "Snuggle Me Warm . . . With Service and Love.";    As 40 quilts were
being completed during the four-hour "old-fashioned quilting bee" program,
guest speakers Pamela Pain of San Jose and Phyllis Ross of Hollister gave
addresses on the value of reaching out to others in need and how quiet acts of
service can make a difference.  </TEXT>
